Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Keith numbers", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
Now we describe a different sort of problem.  Well, it's sort of different. \
That is to say, it looks different. Sort of.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36544212129971*^9, 3.36544219389796*^9}, {
  3.36544265214955*^9, 3.36544265399394*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Around 1987 Michael Keith first wrote about what he called ",
 StyleBox["repfigits",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " (for \"replicating Fibonacci digits\"). These are sequences of numbers \
that, when one progressively addsthem to form new elements in the style of \
the Fibonacci sequence, one obtains the number whose digits began the \
sequence. For example we take the number ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["197", TraditionalForm]]],
 ". We thus start with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "9", ",", "7"}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ". Adding these to get the next element gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "9", ",", "7", ",", "17"}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ". Adding the preceding thee digits to get the next one gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "9", ",", "7", ",", "17", ",", "33"}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 ". If we continue this we get ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
    "1", ",", "9", ",", "7", ",", "17", ",", "33", ",", "57", ",", "107", ",",
      "197", ",", "..."}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ". Because our number, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["197", TraditionalForm]]],
 ", appears in the sequence originating with its digits, it is a repfigit. \
Others later began referring to these as Keith numbers in honor of the first \
to discuss them."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36544212129971*^9, 3.36544219389796*^9}, 
   3.36544265214955*^9}],

Cell["Question: Why do we care about these numbers?", "Text"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

