Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Keith numbers", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
Answer: Beyond the moderate interest of their definition, we want to find \
them because the solution techniques are applicable to other problems. Like \
Frobenius instances/numbers, as we'll see presently.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36543539715355*^9, 3.36543544580105*^9}, {
  3.36544220938297*^9, 3.36544222674458*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A property I find of interest for repfigits is that they are not exactly \
easy to find. By 1994 all and only the ones up to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["15", TraditionalForm]]],
 " digits were known. In 1997 Michael Keith found all of them through ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["19", TraditionalForm]]],
 " digits, using a clever search algorithm and about 500 hours of computer \
time. There are ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["71", TraditionalForm]]],
 " such numbers. No larger ones were known (an unfortunate situation that \
persisted until 2004)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36544225150823*^9, 3.36544232440428*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As it happens, one can write Keith number problems as integer linear \
programs. The digits of a Keith number of a given size will have to satisfy \
one of a few  readily computable linear diophantine equations, subject to the \
obvious inequalities that force them to actually be digits (that is, they \
must be between ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["0", TraditionalForm]]],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["9", TraditionalForm]]],
 " inclusive, with the first being at least ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["1", TraditionalForm]]],
 ")."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36543547814714*^9, 3.36543548245106*^9}}]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

