Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Big Keith numbers", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.36544194185921*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "One will observe that all of these begin with digits in {1,2,9} and end \
with digits in {0,2,4,5,6,7}. If these were in some way \"random\" and \
uniform we would believe the probability of this limited set of first digits \
occuring exclusively to be ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    FractionBox["1", "3"], ")"}], "13"]]],
 ", or about ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FractionBox["1", 
   SuperscriptBox["10", "6"]]]],
 ". The probability of the last digits being so restricted is a tame one\
\[Hyphen]in\[Hyphen]a\[Hyphen]thousand or so. This raises an obvious \
conjecture and a perhaps unusual question: Might there be something \
intrinsically \"interesting\" to Keith numbers that would keep them from \
being \"random\"?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.36544153466495*^9, 3.36544157208644*^9}, {
  3.36544190980559*^9, 3.36544191847857*^9}}]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

